We reiterated our recommendations that Management:

a) . . .;

b) . . .;

c) . . .;

d) Refrain from granting additional cash advances to officers and employees who still have outstanding cash advances; 

e) Require the concerned accountable officer to immediately settle/liquidate the cash advance pertaining to the Intelligence Fund amounting to P200,000.00 following the guidelines and procedures provided under COA Circular No. 2003-003 dated July 30, 2003 as amended by COA-DBM-DILG-Governance Commission for Government Owned and Controlled Corporation (GCG)-Department of National Defense (DND) Joint Circular 2015-01 dated January 8, 2015; and

f) . . .

We further recommended that Management:

a) Refrain from granting special cash advances for operating expenses to officers and employees who are not duly appointed or designated as disbursing officers and who are not properly bonded, and strictly abide with the proper granting of cash advances in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002; and

b) Direct the Municipal Accountant to support cash advance vouchers with his certification that the previous cash advances of concerned accountable officers have been liquidated and accounted for in the books.

We recommended that Management:

a) Ensure optimal utilization of the 20% Development Fund and proper implementation of development projects funded under said fund to achieve the desirable socio-economic targets and outcomes of the LGU;

b) Direct the MPDC in coordination with the Municipal Development Council (MDC) to ensure that the identified projects to be included in the AIP which are sourced from the 20% Development Fund are well-planned and procurement-and-implementation-ready;

c) Direct the MPDC to provide for the specific timeframe or timing of implementation for each development project rather than a uniform and generic timeframe such as January to December of a calendar year for all identified projects; and initiate the procurement procedures of these projects earlier during the calendar year rather than towards the end of the year to avoid delays and/or non-implementation of projects; 

d) . . .; and

e) Consider the reprogramming of continuing appropriations of unimplemented projects which may no longer be needed into other priority development projects.

We recommended the following:

a) The Local Chief Executive, thru the Human Resource Management Office (HRMO), formulate a uniform policy or guidelines in the hiring of JO/COS personnel taking into consideration the LGU’s existing organizational structure, plantilla of personnel, service requirements, financial capability and existing COA, CSC and DBM rules and regulations; and endorse the same to the Office of the Sangguniang Bayan for legislation;

b) The Sangguniang Bayan, upon review and deliberation, institutionalize the policy or guidelines in the hiring of JO/COS personnel by legislating it into an ordinance;

c) The Management require the recording of attendance of JO/COS personnel in the existing biometrics system of the LGU, especially those assigned within or near the premises of the Municipal Hall. Otherwise, at least require the recording of attendance in permanent logbooks for JO/COS personnel assigned in the field or far from the premises of the Municipal Hall, indicating their names and signatures as well as the time of arrival at and departure from their place of assignment;

d) The HRMO, in coordination with respective Heads of Offices/Departments, properly monitor and validate the attendance and actual accomplishments of JO/COS personnel; 

e) The Local Chief Executive and/or the Municipal Vice Mayor use the appropriate form of or type of contract or agreement in the hiring of JO personnel which includes the signature of the concerned JO personnel as acceptance or acknowledgment of the stipulations of the job order contract or agreement; and

f) The HRMO carry out a periodic orientation/reorientation for JO/COS personnel on various rules and regulations on human resource, as well as, the terms and agreements of their employment.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Prepare the corresponding journal entries in the books of the GF relative to the journal entries made during CY 2023 affecting the Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds accounts in the books of TF and SEF;
Prepare the proper adjusting entries by reverting the entries made relative to the transfer of unexpended balances of LDRRMF for CYs 2016 and 2017 since the actual cash was not transferred, and if transferred, the same should have been reverted back to the GF, five years after the same was transferred from the GF to the STF;
Review journal entries made relative to the loan counterpart of the LGU for the DAR Irrigation Project which were transferred from the GF to the TF which should have been recorded as “Transfers from General Fund of LGU Counterpart/Equity Share” instead of “Due from Other Funds” in the GF, and as “Trust Liability” instead of “Due to Other Funds” in the TF; and
Exert efforts to verify the journal entries made from CY 2014 to CY 2022 which resulted to the discrepancies between the reciprocal accounts, Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds, reconcile the same, and effect the necessary adjustments, as warranted, to reflect the correct account balances for fair presentation of accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended the following:
The GSO prepare the RIS to support every issuance of supplies and inventories to requisitioning units or end-users; prepare and submit the SSMI weekly to the Accounting Unit as basis for the recording of related expenses using the prescribed format provided under the Manual on NGAS for LGUs;
The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain complete Supply Ledger Cards, and conduct periodic reconciliation with the property/supply records and the result of physical count of inventories;
The GSO prepare and maintain complete Stock Cards, and conduct periodic reconciliation with the accounting records and the result of physical count of inventories;
The Local Chief Executive reconstitute its Inventory Committee and include in its duties and responsibilities the conduct of physical count of inventories on hand;
The Inventory Committee conduct the physical count of inventories at least semi-annually, prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to the Office of the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year;
The GSO in coordination with the Municipal Accountant and the Inventory Committee, examine the existence of the reported inventory account balances, prepare and submit the corresponding SSMI, together with the duly accomplished RIS, as basis for the recording of the necessary expenses/adjustments;
The Municipal Accountant fully observe the perpetual inventory method in the recording/accounting of inventories, wherein purchases are recorded into their respective inventory accounts upon initial recognition, and thereafter expensed upon issuance to end-users;
For bulk purchases of supplies, materials and semi-expendable properties/equipment, the Municipal Accountant properly identify and record separately the purchased items into their appropriate inventory accounts rather than initially recording the whole bulk purchase as Office Supplies Inventory;
Management set-up an internal policy that requires the RHU to submit inventory reports either on a monthly, quarterly or semestral basis, in order for the Municipal Accountant to have a timely recording of related expenses pertaining to consumed or distributed Drugs and Medicines Inventory and Medical, Dental and Laboratory Supplies Inventory; and
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entries to record the Solar Powered 4G Camera Kit with cost of P99,800.00 into its appropriate PPE account. Also, compute for the depreciation expenses and accumulated depreciation of said item and effect the adjusting entries in the books of accounts to reflect the proper carrying amount of the PPE item.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Accountant, Inventory Committee and GSO identify the variances of PPE account balances between the accounting records and the result of the physical count, and reconcile such variances to facilitate the proper recording/reporting of PPE account balances in the books of accounts of the LGU;
The Inventory Committee include in the physical count and the RPCPPE the Construction in Progress accounts;
The Inventory Committee verify the existence of Medical Equipment amounting to P1.804 million which was included in the RPCPPE but was not provided with description, property number and quantity;
The Inventory Committee exclude the balances of Merchandise Inventory and report the same in the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories with complete details as to inventory number, unit of measure, and quantity;
The GSO prepare and maintain property cards for each PPE and reconcile the same with the accounting records and the result of the physical count;
The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain complete PPE Ledger Cards, and reconcile the same with the property records and the results of the physical count; and
The Municipal Accountant exert effort to trace back prior years’ records and identify the unidentified balances of CIP accounts amounting to P5.883 million and Land Improvements amounting to P97,163.40, and/or derecognize these account balances, if warranted, following the guidelines and procedures for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts prescribed under COA Circular No. COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended the following:
The GSO, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, conduct physical count of the unused water supply materials and submit the result to the Municipal Accountant and the Office of the Auditor;
The GSO take custody of the unused water supply materials, and observe the proper handling and issuance of these items to end-users through the preparation of RIS and SSMI;
The Municipal Accountant effect the necessary adjustments to record the Construction Materials Inventory pertaining to the unused water supply materials. Relative thereto, the equivalent cost will be dropped from the Water Supply Systems account;
The Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, compute for the carrying amounts of the replaced parts of the Water Supply Systems, and derecognize the same pursuant to Paragraph 85 of IPSAS 17; and
The Municipal Engineer prepare progress accomplishment reports and certificates of completion for the actual cost of repairs and maintenance as basis for the capitalization of these costs into the Water Supply Systems and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant and the Office of the Auditor.

We recommended that Management:
Send demand letters to concerned accountable officers and employees with outstanding cash advances for the immediate liquidation and/or settlement of their accounts. In case of non-liquidation and/or non-settlement, cause the withholding of salaries or any money claims due them;
Take appropriate actions on the unsettled accounts of accountable officers who are no longer connected or not in active service with the LGU;
Conduct regular monitoring and strict enforcement of controls in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances. Strictly enforce the prescribed period for the liquidation of cash advances as provided under COA Circular No. 97-002 to ensure the timely recognition of expenses thereof;
Refrain from granting additional cash advances to officers and employees who still have outstanding cash advances;
Require the Municipal Accountant to issue a certification that previous cash advances have been fully liquidated and accounted for in the books before the grant of a new cash advance;
Require the concerned accountable officer to immediately settle/liquidate the cash advance pertaining to the Intelligence Fund amounting to P200,000.00 following the guidelines and procedures provided under COA Circular No. 2003-003 dated July 30, 2003 as amended by COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular 2015-01 dated January 8, 2015; and
Consider the request for write-off of dormant unliquidated cash advances of accountable officers, who are no longer connected with the LGU, following the guidelines, procedures and documentary requirements pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 and/or COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023, as applicable.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator conduct monitoring and evaluation on the status of implementation of barangay development projects which were funded from the 20 per cent Development Fund for CYs 2021 and 2022 of the LGU, and submit a status report of the same to the Office of the Auditor;
The Management compel the concerned barangays to fully implement the intended projects, utilize the funds transferred to them, and liquidate said funds for proper recording in the books of accounts of the LGU and the barangays and/or demand/require the refund of funds in case of failure of the barangays to implement the intended projects;
The Management improve the stipulations under the MOA for any subsequent fund transfers to barangays by including stipulations on the period of project implementation, period of submission of project accomplishment reports and liquidation documents, and conditions/penalties/remedies in case of failure of the barangay to implement the project and utilize the fund;
The Municipal Accountant effect the necessary adjustment to record the Due from LGU for the disbursement paid under DV No. 100-2212-2513 dated December 28, 2022 to Barangay Guling in the amount of P138,000.00 for the concreting of barangay perimeter fence which was erroneously recorded as Transfers for Project Equity Share/LGU Counterpart in CY 2022; and
The Municipal Account refrain from granting additional fund transfers to barangays with outstanding or unliquidated fund transfers, and issue a certification that funds previously transferred to the barangay has been liquidated and accounted for in the books to be attached to the disbursement voucher.

We recommended that:
Management take full opportunity on the application of COA Circular No. 2020-006 and fully comply with the prescribed guidelines and procedures, particularly the conduct of physical count of PPE, the recognition of PPE items found at station, the disposition of non-existing/missing PPE items, the procedures in the derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability, and the recording of accounting entries and disclosures in the notes to financial statements, for the purpose of one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of the LGU;
The Local Chief Executive reconstitute the LGU’s Inventory Committee to include at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Units;
The Inventory Committee prepare the PIP, to be approved by the local chief executive and submit the approved PIP to the Office of the Auditor at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities;
The Inventory Committee assign a unique property number for each PPE item following the prescribed identification/numbering system provided in Section 5.6 of the Circular;
The Inventory Committee record/document daily the physical count using the ICF for each PPE sub-major account group and use the ICF as basis in the preparation of the RPCPPE;
The Property Unit prepare a List of PPEs Found at Station (Annex B of the Circular), prepare property cards for PPE items found at station, and submit the list to the Accounting Unit as basis for the recording in the books of accounts; and
The Property Unit prepare a List of Non-Existing/Missing PPEs (Annex C of the Circular) and follow the procedures for the disposition of the non-existing/missing PPE items provided under Sections 7 and 8 of the Circular, as applicable.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant effect the necessary adjustments to reclassify the carrying amounts of the subject issued semi-expendable properties from the respective PPE accounts into the Prior Period Adjustments account;
The Municipal Accountant observe the capitalization threshold of P50,000.00 on a per item basis, and not on the total cost of the bulk acquisitions;
The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain the SPLCs to record promptly the acquisition, description, custody, impairment, issue/transfer/disposal, repair history, and other information about the property;
The Municipal Accountant ensure that disbursement vouchers relative to the payment of issued semi-expendable properties are supported with ICS for proper and complete documentation;
The Municipal Accountant or the GSO submit to the Office of the Auditor the lacking ICS of the subject disbursement vouchers;
The GSO prepare and maintain the SPCs to record promptly the acquisition, issue/transfer/disposal and the description/information about the asset;
The GSO prepare and issue to end-users the ICS in its prescribed form, provide separate control numbers for each ICS for low-valued items and high-valued items, and maintain the same in a sequential manner/order; and
The GSO prepare and maintain the RegSPI to record promptly the issue, return, reissue, disposal, and other information about the property if returned and the description/information about the asset.

We recommended the following:
The Property Unit/General Services Officer prepare the IIRUP in its prescribed form for all unserviceable properties, and the WMR for all waste materials, subject for disposal, and submit the same to the Disposal Committee;
The Management assign a designated area or location for the storage of unserviceable properties subject for disposal. Thereafter, require the accountable officers or end-users to turn-over the unserviceable properties to the General Services Officer for safekeeping and custody;
The Management, thru the Local Chief Executive, create a Disposal Committee whose functions include the inspection, appraisal and disposal of unserviceable properties;
The Disposal Committee, after its creation, conduct inspection and appraisal and set the final appraised values of all unserviceable properties subject for disposal, as identified and reported in the IIRUP. The appraised values shall be considered as the minimum selling price so that the LGU will receive fair compensation for the items sold;
The Management submit to the Office of the Auditor a written letter, together with the IIRUP, appraisal report and other pertinent documents, requesting for technical evaluation of the appraised values of the unserviceable properties as determined by the Disposal Committee, which will be endorsed by the latter to the COA IX Technical Audit Group for their independent evaluation;
The Disposal Committee determine the appropriate mode of disposal and undertake the disposal proceedings in accordance with the revised manual on the disposal of government properties; and
Pending commencement and completion of disposal procedures, the Municipal Accountant, with the assistance of the Appraisal Committee, estimate the recoverable service amounts of unserviceable PPE items, and thereafter compute and recognize its impairment losses, if any, for fair presentation of accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that:
Management ensure optimal utilization of the 20 per cent Development Fund and proper implementation of development projects funded under said fund to achieve the desirable socio-economic targets and outcomes of the LGU;
The MPDC, in coordination with the Municipal Development Council (MDC), to ensure that identified projects to be included in the AIP which are sourced from the 20 per cent Development Fund are well-planned and procurement-and-implementation-ready;
The MPDC, in coordination with the MDC, to prepare a supplemental investment program for any realignment of funds affecting the 20 per cent Development Fund and submit the same to the local sanggunian for approval;
The MPDC provide for the specific timeframe or timing of implementation for each development project rather than a uniform and generic timeframe such as January to December of a calendar year for all identified projects; and initiate the procurement procedures of these projects earlier during the calendar year rather than towards the end of the year to avoid delays and/or non-implementation of projects;
The Municipal Budget Officer to trace and verify their records relative to the current and continuing appropriations for the 20 per cent Development Fund, and submit a report of the status and actual balances of the same to the Office of the Auditor, including justifications on the discrepancies noted for the unexpended balances of appropriations per audit and per budget records/reports; and
The Municipal Budget Officer refrain from approving obligations without available appropriations and/or supplemental budgets. Further, the Municipal Budget Officer observe proper control and monitoring to ensure that funds are utilized exclusively for the specific purpose for which they have been appropriated, otherwise, legal sanctions shall be imposed for its continued incurrence.

We recommended that Management:
Develop the Solid Waste Disposal Site of the LGU to conform with the requirements of law and stop the operation of the open dumpsite for its garbage disposal;
Direct the MENRO-Designate to properly utilize the MRF and RCA which has been inoperative, and closely monitor the proper maintenance of the MRF and RCA;
Install security fence and designate a personnel/caretaker assigned at the Solid Waste Disposal Site to prevent illegal entries and trespassing;
Intensify Information, Education and Communication (IEC) campaign to disseminate information to the public regarding programs, plans and activities of the LGU pursuant to its Solid Waste Management and to inform and educate them of the provisions in RA No. 9003 and their responsibilities as waste generators;
Require the solid waste collectors to be equipped with proper and adequate protective equipment;
Install appropriate compartments on the vehicles used for the collection and transport of solid wastes to facilitate efficient storing of sorted wastes while in transit; and
Strictly enforce the fines and penalties in accordance with Section 49 of RA No. 9003 and Section 41 of Municipal Ordinance No. 05-2008.

We recommended that Management:
Through the Sangguniang Bayan, prioritize the passage of an ordinance authorizing the LGU to generate and collect revenue from the sale of subdivided lots;
Cease the sale of remaining subdivided lots and the collection of revenue therefrom pending the enactment of an ordinance authorizing the LGU to generate and collect such revenue source;
Adopt effective strategies to sell the remaining subdivided lots to interested buyers to generate additional income of the LGU; and
Consider adjusting the selling price of the remaining lots available for sale to reflect the current market value of P600.00 per square meter.

We recommended the following: (a) The Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant at the beginning of the year a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year which will serve as basis of the latter for the booking up of the RPT and SET Receivable accounts;

b) The Municipal Accountant submit to the Office of the Auditor the Journal Entry Voucher to set up the RPT and SET Receivables together with the certified list of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year;

c) . . .; and

d) The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for each type of real property subjected to RPT to support the controlling account in the general ledger of the RPT Receivable account.

We recommended the following:

a) The Municipal Engineer furnish the Municipal Accountant copies of the Certificate of Completion, approved program of works and other pertinent documents as basis for the reclassification of accounts for completed projects;

b) The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entries to properly reclassify the cost of materials and costs of labor of the completed infrastructure assets from the CIP account to the School Building account;

c) The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entries to properly reclassify the cost of unused construction materials from the CIP account to the Construction Materials Inventory account; and

d) . . .

We recommended the following:

a) The Management, in coordination with concerned contractors, initiate measures and strategies to fast track the completion of ongoing infrastructure projects such as provision of additional manpower and materials, and strict/close supervision of project works; 

b) The Management ensure timely implementation of infrastructure projects thru effective monitoring of the performance of contractors; adopt calibrated measures as provided under GPPB Circular No. 03-2019 dated 8 March 2019 particularly when contractors incur negative slippage during the contract duration;

c) The Municipal Engineer prepare the Statement of Time Elapsed showing the status of project implementation with regards to the contract duration and attach the same to every progress and final billings of contractors; and

d) The Municipal Accountant, with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer, exert effort in the computation of liquidated damages arising from the delays incurred by contractors in the implementation of infrastructure projects, and deduct/collect the same from the retention money, other securities posted by contractors, or from any money due or which may become due the contractors, whichever is available to the Management.

We recommended the following:

a)	The Municipal Treasurer prepare the RIS to support every issuance of supplies and inventories to requisitioning units or end-users; prepare and submit the SSMI to the Accounting Unit as basis for the recording of related expenses; 

