We recommended that Management:

a)	Strictly comply with the procurement rules, regulations and procedures of competitive bidding and/or alternative modes of procurement as provided under the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 regardless of the mode of payment; 

b)	Cause the payment of procurements directly to the supplier thru check; 

c) . . .; and

d)	Effect the withholding of taxes for payment of any procurement of goods and services.

We recommended the following:

a) Send demand letters to concerned accountable officers and employees with outstanding cash advances for the immediate liquidation and/or settlement of their accounts. In case of non-liquidation and/or non-settlement, cause the withholding of salaries or any money claims due them;

b) 	Refrain from granting additional cash advances to officers and employees who still have outstanding cash advances. Cash advances for the government programs/activities must be granted only to eligible officers and employees;

c) 	Take appropriate actions on the unsettled accounts of accountable officers who are no longer connected or not in active service with the LGU and/or request for write-off of dormant accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, if warranted;

d) 	Regular monitoring and strict enforcement of controls in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances. Strictly enforce the prescribed period for the liquidation of cash advances as provided under COA Circular No. 97-002 to ensure the timely recognition of expenses thereof;

f) 	Advances for Payroll account amounting to P2.476 million pertaining to the cash advance of the previous Municipal Treasurer, who has already retired from the service, be reclassified to Other Receivables account for fair presentation in the financial statements since the asset was lost due to the robbery incident and the corresponding request for relief of accountability was denied and became final and executory.

We recommended that Management:

a) 	Direct the Municipal SWM Board to develop a current and updated 10-year Municipal SWM Plan, submit the same to the Provincial Solid Waste Management Board for review and subsequent approval by the National Solid Waste Management Commission;

b) 	Stop the operation of the open dumpsite for its garbage disposal.

We recommend that the Local Chief Executive implement strictly the provisions of the Manual on Audit for Fuel Consumption of Government Motor Vehicles prescribed in COA Circular No. 77-6l dated September 26, 1977 for effective control of gasoline, oil and lubricant expenditures;

•  Concerned officials with government vehicles and the Municipal Engineer prepare and submit regularly thru the Municipal Accountant to the Office of the Auditor the Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption and Monthly Report of Official Travels.  Exercise control over the use of government vehicles through properly accomplished and duly approved and serially numbered Driver’s Trip Tickets;

•  The Municipal Accountant be required to verify into the completeness of the supporting documents before signing the DVs.  Claims with incomplete supporting documents must be returned to the claimant before payment be made; and

•  Charging of fuel consumed by private vehicles be stopped.

We recommend that the LGU:

•  Reevaluate its financial capabilities in sustaining the JHCSC-ESU Guipos;

•  Enact ordinance for the creation of the JHCSC-ESU Guipos;

•  Refrain from disbursing honoraria to LGU officials and employees in the administration of the JHSCS-ESU Guipos;

•  Withheld appropriate taxes on the honoraria and the salaries of the officials and instructors, and

•  Seek assistance with CHED in addressing what was lacking in the external studies unit.
